==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*apala-'', from Indo-European ''*abl-, *ablu-''.  Cognate with Old Frisian [[appel]], Old Saxon [[appel]] (Dutch [[appel]]), Old High German [[apful]] (German [[Apfel]]), Old Norse [[epli]] (Swedish [[äpple]]), Crimean Gothic ''apel''.  The IE root is also the source of Old Irish [[ubull]] (Irish [[úll]]), Lithuanian [[obuolys]], Common Slavonic ''jabl’ko'' (Russian [[яблоко]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'æppel/

===Noun===
'''æppel''' ''m''
# a [[fruit]], especially an [[apple]]
#:''Æppel unsælga, deaþ-beames ofet.''  The unblessed apple, fruit of the tree of death. (Cædmon’s ''Metrical Paraphrase'')
# an [[apple-tree]]

